5/13 - the isle of birth

The days are constricting - the climate of the crew is akin to the end of a heavy storm - skies not quite clear. The fatigue is evident. I foresee a shift in wind soon. Captain Aaron assures us land is approaching. I’ve tried to subdue my self and remain content with the incessant swaying, but I must admit, my heart is relieved by the prospect of docking.

____

I stopped and dived into the rush of memory - frame after frame strewn out across the floor of my mind. The ship the pharmacy the pharmacy my health my family the ship the ship the house the house the nation the sea - all of it softly and subtely and menacingly rocking back and forth.

I have yet to speak my intent clearly, but as soon as land is reached I fear it will be time for me to strike out again. The colors of this passage are running off the canvas and it’s time for me to repaint.
1:35 AM
a momentary reflection

You see… I could feign this sense of continuity and coherence - put up this facade that a narrative thread were weaving the loose vignettes together - but I’d be a liar. And a liar has no place on this ship - as ironic as that may seem.

A loosely strung gang of people heading towards an ill defined goal - at times uncertain, at time unwavering along the way.

And let me clarify - there is no CONSCIOUS thread. As to whether in the ultimate end it will all have appeared nice and sequential to you (the reader) I will leave an unresolved matter.

Just know that the tralfamadorians taught me something valuable;

“There isn’t any particular relationship between the messages, except that the author has chosen them carefully, so that, when seen all at once, they produce an image of life that is beautiful and surprising and deep. There is no beginning, no middle, no end, no suspense, no moral, no causes, no effects. What we love in our books are the depths of many marvelous moments seen all at one time.” (footnote)
