3:03 PM
sullen wandering

I was sullenly walking down the street one night, after one of those moments where the sandstorm of thought dies down and you’re left with standing in an open field. As usual, my head slightly bent down, feet coming in and out of view, rocks, gum, shoelaces, leaves, water, a shimmer. It was only a few paces after that it registered, I turned back and there it was, a tiny, nondescript shimmering speck…. I had never seen anything like that before. I tried to pick it up but nothing happened. I stood entranced for a moment, thought I must be delusional - I mean my head is never this quiet.. something must be up, yea? I carried on, but the rest of the walk seemed a tinge less worthwhile. I turned and went back home, repeatedly glancing back to see it was still there.

Anyhow, months passed, experiences piled on and the impressions from that night dulled. Until. Until one day I was sitting on the bus midday on my way back home from work. I had a book in my backpack I was mechanically reading, I decided not to open it up now though. I just wanted to stop being for a second. That’s when this women walked on the bus and sat in the row across from me. Too stunned yet again to really verbalize to myself what was happening. There the shimmer was, just kinda resting there on the end of her purse. I had to fight myself from trying to touch it. I wanted to ask her, but I thought to myself “she must know it’s there… right?” A glance to my left and there was an old man with the faint trace of a smile just sitting there. He didn’t seem to notice anything. Whatever…

then a series of dreams. then people started appearing in my life out of nowhere. then I lost everything. sitting in a holding cell somewhere in the backwoods of fucking virigina I’m looking at the ceiling and there it is. I reached up and sort of morphed into some weird ethereal being, but I was back on that walk, and back on the bus, and back in the library, and back in the cell. I knew absolutely that no one else could see this torturous whatever it was. So i internally resolved to renounce the currents of the phenomenal world around me and investigate whatever this thing was.

By it’s very nature I can’t tell you what it is. I can’t tell you what it’s not. I can’t tell you where it is. I can’t tell you where it’s not. I can’t speak about it. I can only speak/write around it. Not that I encompass it, not that it’s defined. Something like an aleph. Or the impression of counting without numbers or seeing without eyes or. something…. It’s something for certain. Can’t say for sure. Almost like a thread. one you begin tugging at, aiming to find the root. I’m still finding the root. I’m convinced there is no root. But i’m not convinced enough to abandon the tugging. Each inch reveals more. So I continue.

It’s something akin to climbing stairs, but as soon as you reach your desired floor you realize you’re only still on the bottom floor staring up at the stairs. Or more like, “you’re in a box” then you’re the box inside yourself. then the inner and outer box are really the same box but you’re still standing from inside it. Or maybe more like….

I don’t know…. this shimmer…. this faint little speck.

Grains of sand in infinitude
what similitude shall embrace?
cosmic grains juxtaposed with that
life giving lamp on the beach of eternity
The light of oneness pervades the sea, or
rather grains adrift in ethereal light
Light upon Light - what dim reflection,
what small conception can we attain?
Of that grand architect - adrift in
the grand design, a course inscribed through time
Each grain a shore with infinitely more
atoms of reflected light
and what a delight it certainly is
to reflect on eternal light
6:49 PM
destruction of knowledge/beginning of ayn yaqin [41;53]

Billy finds his way into the central library of New Alexandria - considered the crown jewel of the world’s knowledge, the epicenter of learning and culture.

Book after book begins to run, trickle, words, characters down the page like sweat drops. in and out of focus. little puzzle pieces tearing at the seams and crumbling. into ash. being carried down gently by a non existent wind. page after page merging into oblivion. his fingers combing and sifting as if trying to hold onto waters of life. in vain. book after book. his pace increased. heart rate. the sand returning, rising up around his feet. the adjoining shelves heat intesifying. the illusion of this realm crumbling. He had found the loose thread that was dangling and began pulling and would now not cease pulling until the whole fabric unravelled. The sand was up to his knees. Dragging along in incoherence he continued sifting and pouring… not a single word or verse registered.

This the womb of knowledge?

Could this really be what the merchants praised so highly?
